2.4212713531902983

To reiterate, I'm calculating the significance by:

  1. Finding the area of the uncut qcd and higgs
  2. Finding the area of the cut qcd and higgs
  3. Finding the fraction cut/uncut
  4. cut/uncut * expected yield to get Nqcd and Nhiggs
  5. Plug that into the formula Nhiggs/sqrt(Nqcd)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,1)
qcd_values, qcd_bins, _ = ax.hist(qcd_cut,   bins=100, label='qcd')



higgs_values, higgs_bins, _ = ax.hist(higgs_cut, bins=100, label='higgs')
data_values, data_bins, _ = ax.hist(data_cut,  bins=100, label='data')


#ax.hist([qcd_cut, higgs["mass"]], density=True, stacked=True, bins=100)
y = 0

qcd_area = sum(np.diff(qcd_bins)*qcd_values)
higgs_area = sum(np.diff(higgs_bins) * higgs_values)
data_area = sum(np.diff(data_bins) * data_values)
ax.legend(prop={'size': 100})
print((higgs_area*100/uncut_higgs_area) / math.sqrt(20000 * data_area/uncut_data_area))

plt.show()

0.4901556089625626

The significance is low because the high luminosity data set looks a lot like the background data set. Hence the N(high luminosity) / N(Qcd) is low.
